</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Oncologic, reconstructive, and cosmetic breast surgery has evolved in the last 20 years. Familiarity with cutting-edge surgical techniques and their imaging characteristics is essential for radiologic interpretation and may help avert false-positive imaging findings. Novel surgical techniques include skin- and nipple-sparing mastectomies, autologous free flaps, autologous fat grafting, and nipple-areola–complex breast reconstruction. These techniques are illustrated and compared with conventional surgical techniques, including modified radical mastectomy and autologous pedicled flaps. The role of magnetic resonance (MR) imaging in surgical planning, evaluation for complications, and postsurgical cancer detection is described. Breast reconstruction and augmentation using silicone gel–filled implants is discussed in light of the Food and Drug Administration’s recommendation for MR imaging screening for “silent” implant rupture 3 years after implantation and every 2 years thereafter. Recent developments in skin incision techniques for reduction mammoplasty are presented. The effects of postsurgical changes on the detection of breast cancer are discussed by type of surgery.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.343135059">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.343135059">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig1.jpeg" height="1605" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Diagram shows the surgical incisions (dashed red lines) used for modified radical mastectomy (MRM), skin-sparing mastectomy, and nipple-sparing mastectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig2a.jpeg" height="544" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> MR imaging findings after MRM. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image in a 67-year-old woman 8 years after right MRM and 1 year after radiation treatment for cancer recurrence in the chest wall shows enhancement of the subcutaneous fat in the right chest (arrow), a finding compatible with radiation change. The pectoralis major <i>(M)</i> and minor <i>(m)</i> muscles are thickened in the right breast compared with the left breast. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image in a 64-year-old woman 12 years after left MRM who presented with a palpable mass in the left chest wall shows a mass (<b>*</b>) between the pectoralis major and minor muscles, a finding proved at biopsy to be infiltrating adenocarcinoma. Compared with the contralateral side, there is marked heterogeneous enhancement of the lateral pectoralis major muscle (arrow), a finding consistent with tumor invasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig2b.jpeg" height="544" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> MR imaging findings after MRM. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image in a 67-year-old woman 8 years after right MRM and 1 year after radiation treatment for cancer recurrence in the chest wall shows enhancement of the subcutaneous fat in the right chest (arrow), a finding compatible with radiation change. The pectoralis major <i>(M)</i> and minor <i>(m)</i> muscles are thickened in the right breast compared with the left breast. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image in a 64-year-old woman 12 years after left MRM who presented with a palpable mass in the left chest wall shows a mass (<b>*</b>) between the pectoralis major and minor muscles, a finding proved at biopsy to be infiltrating adenocarcinoma. Compared with the contralateral side, there is marked heterogeneous enhancement of the lateral pectoralis major muscle (arrow), a finding consistent with tumor invasion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig3a.jpeg" height="705" width="859" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Imaging findings in the left breast of a 54-year-old woman before and after skin-sparing mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows pleomorphic calcifications (circled) extending to the NAC. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images show a 4.0-cm area of nonmass enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>), with an additional mass 1.2 cm from the NAC (arrow in <b>c</b>). After intraoperative biopsy of the NAC confirmed IDC, the NAC was removed, and skin-sparing mastectomy with a free transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous (TRAM) flap and NAC reconstruction was performed. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction image shows abdominal fat subjacent to the native breast skin and subcutaneous fat, a normal finding after skin-sparing mastectomy. A thin contact line (arrow) is seen separating the native fat from the TRAM flap. Fibroglandular features are seen subjacent to the native skin inferiorly (arrowhead) and should be reported by the radiologist.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig3b.jpeg" height="705" width="716" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Imaging findings in the left breast of a 54-year-old woman before and after skin-sparing mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows pleomorphic calcifications (circled) extending to the NAC. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images show a 4.0-cm area of nonmass enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>), with an additional mass 1.2 cm from the NAC (arrow in <b>c</b>). After intraoperative biopsy of the NAC confirmed IDC, the NAC was removed, and skin-sparing mastectomy with a free transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous (TRAM) flap and NAC reconstruction was performed. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction image shows abdominal fat subjacent to the native breast skin and subcutaneous fat, a normal finding after skin-sparing mastectomy. A thin contact line (arrow) is seen separating the native fat from the TRAM flap. Fibroglandular features are seen subjacent to the native skin inferiorly (arrowhead) and should be reported by the radiologist.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig3c.jpeg" height="862" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Imaging findings in the left breast of a 54-year-old woman before and after skin-sparing mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows pleomorphic calcifications (circled) extending to the NAC. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images show a 4.0-cm area of nonmass enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>), with an additional mass 1.2 cm from the NAC (arrow in <b>c</b>). After intraoperative biopsy of the NAC confirmed IDC, the NAC was removed, and skin-sparing mastectomy with a free transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous (TRAM) flap and NAC reconstruction was performed. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction image shows abdominal fat subjacent to the native breast skin and subcutaneous fat, a normal finding after skin-sparing mastectomy. A thin contact line (arrow) is seen separating the native fat from the TRAM flap. Fibroglandular features are seen subjacent to the native skin inferiorly (arrowhead) and should be reported by the radiologist.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig3d.jpeg" height="862" width="746" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Imaging findings in the left breast of a 54-year-old woman before and after skin-sparing mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC). <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows pleomorphic calcifications (circled) extending to the NAC. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR images show a 4.0-cm area of nonmass enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>), with an additional mass 1.2 cm from the NAC (arrow in <b>c</b>). After intraoperative biopsy of the NAC confirmed IDC, the NAC was removed, and skin-sparing mastectomy with a free transverse rectus abdominis myocutaneous (TRAM) flap and NAC reconstruction was performed. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction image shows abdominal fat subjacent to the native breast skin and subcutaneous fat, a normal finding after skin-sparing mastectomy. A thin contact line (arrow) is seen separating the native fat from the TRAM flap. Fibroglandular features are seen subjacent to the native skin inferiorly (arrowhead) and should be reported by the radiologist.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig4a.jpeg" height="1122" width="568" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Imaging findings before and after nipple-sparing mastectomy with superior gluteal artery perforator reconstruction in a 56-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows clustered heterogeneous calcifications in the upper outer left breast (circled). <b>(b)</b> Postoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows replacement of the glandular tissue with fat, with preservation of the NAC. <b>(c, d)</b> Preoperative <b>(c)</b> and postoperative <b>(d)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted images show postoperative maintenance of the classic peripheral enhancement of the NAC and replacement of the glandular tissue with gluteal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig4b.jpeg" height="1123" width="557" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Imaging findings before and after nipple-sparing mastectomy with superior gluteal artery perforator reconstruction in a 56-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows clustered heterogeneous calcifications in the upper outer left breast (circled). <b>(b)</b> Postoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows replacement of the glandular tissue with fat, with preservation of the NAC. <b>(c, d)</b> Preoperative <b>(c)</b> and postoperative <b>(d)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted images show postoperative maintenance of the classic peripheral enhancement of the NAC and replacement of the glandular tissue with gluteal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig4c.jpeg" height="995" width="654" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Imaging findings before and after nipple-sparing mastectomy with superior gluteal artery perforator reconstruction in a 56-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows clustered heterogeneous calcifications in the upper outer left breast (circled). <b>(b)</b> Postoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows replacement of the glandular tissue with fat, with preservation of the NAC. <b>(c, d)</b> Preoperative <b>(c)</b> and postoperative <b>(d)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted images show postoperative maintenance of the classic peripheral enhancement of the NAC and replacement of the glandular tissue with gluteal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig4d.jpeg" height="995" width="673" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Imaging findings before and after nipple-sparing mastectomy with superior gluteal artery perforator reconstruction in a 56-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows clustered heterogeneous calcifications in the upper outer left breast (circled). <b>(b)</b> Postoperative mediolateral oblique mammogram shows replacement of the glandular tissue with fat, with preservation of the NAC. <b>(c, d)</b> Preoperative <b>(c)</b> and postoperative <b>(d)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted images show postoperative maintenance of the classic peripheral enhancement of the NAC and replacement of the glandular tissue with gluteal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig5a.jpeg" height="1120" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Pedicled TRAM flap. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the contralateral rectus abdominis muscle tunneled through the inframammary fold to the mastectomy pocket. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r32" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r32">32</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Axial three-dimensional maximum intensity projection image shows the perforating vessels from the superior epigastric artery within the vascular pedicle in a right TRAM flap. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image shows the rectus abdominis muscle folded within the breast pocket, with an atrophic appearance (arrows). The superior epigastric artery is tunneled into the breast pocket and is seen as a flow void in the center of the rectus abdominis muscle (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig5b.jpeg" height="784" width="1094" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Pedicled TRAM flap. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the contralateral rectus abdominis muscle tunneled through the inframammary fold to the mastectomy pocket. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r32" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r32">32</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Axial three-dimensional maximum intensity projection image shows the perforating vessels from the superior epigastric artery within the vascular pedicle in a right TRAM flap. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image shows the rectus abdominis muscle folded within the breast pocket, with an atrophic appearance (arrows). The superior epigastric artery is tunneled into the breast pocket and is seen as a flow void in the center of the rectus abdominis muscle (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig5c.jpeg" height="785" width="674" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Pedicled TRAM flap. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows the contralateral rectus abdominis muscle tunneled through the inframammary fold to the mastectomy pocket. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r32" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r32">32</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Axial three-dimensional maximum intensity projection image shows the perforating vessels from the superior epigastric artery within the vascular pedicle in a right TRAM flap. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image shows the rectus abdominis muscle folded within the breast pocket, with an atrophic appearance (arrows). The superior epigastric artery is tunneled into the breast pocket and is seen as a flow void in the center of the rectus abdominis muscle (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig6a.jpeg" height="1505" width="877" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Creation of right deep inferior epigastric perforator (DIEP) flap after right MRM. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the skin markings for right DIEP flap reconstruction and left breast reduction (vertical scar technique). <b>(b)</b> In this intraoperative photograph, the internal mammary artery and vein are identified at the level of the right second through fourth ribs; this area serves as the pocket for the DIEP flap and the site for recipient vessel anastamosis. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows the bilateral inferior epigastric vascular perforator vessels being harvested with skin and fat from the abdomen. <b>(d</b>) Postoperative photograph shows the final result, with a skin island conforming to the right mastectomy defect. Note the lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision used for the left breast reduction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig6b.jpeg" height="489" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Creation of right deep inferior epigastric perforator (DIEP) flap after right MRM. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the skin markings for right DIEP flap reconstruction and left breast reduction (vertical scar technique). <b>(b)</b> In this intraoperative photograph, the internal mammary artery and vein are identified at the level of the right second through fourth ribs; this area serves as the pocket for the DIEP flap and the site for recipient vessel anastamosis. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows the bilateral inferior epigastric vascular perforator vessels being harvested with skin and fat from the abdomen. <b>(d</b>) Postoperative photograph shows the final result, with a skin island conforming to the right mastectomy defect. Note the lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision used for the left breast reduction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig6c.jpeg" height="531" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Creation of right deep inferior epigastric perforator (DIEP) flap after right MRM. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the skin markings for right DIEP flap reconstruction and left breast reduction (vertical scar technique). <b>(b)</b> In this intraoperative photograph, the internal mammary artery and vein are identified at the level of the right second through fourth ribs; this area serves as the pocket for the DIEP flap and the site for recipient vessel anastamosis. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows the bilateral inferior epigastric vascular perforator vessels being harvested with skin and fat from the abdomen. <b>(d</b>) Postoperative photograph shows the final result, with a skin island conforming to the right mastectomy defect. Note the lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision used for the left breast reduction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig6d.jpeg" height="335" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> Creation of right deep inferior epigastric perforator (DIEP) flap after right MRM. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the skin markings for right DIEP flap reconstruction and left breast reduction (vertical scar technique). <b>(b)</b> In this intraoperative photograph, the internal mammary artery and vein are identified at the level of the right second through fourth ribs; this area serves as the pocket for the DIEP flap and the site for recipient vessel anastamosis. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows the bilateral inferior epigastric vascular perforator vessels being harvested with skin and fat from the abdomen. <b>(d</b>) Postoperative photograph shows the final result, with a skin island conforming to the right mastectomy defect. Note the lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision used for the left breast reduction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig7.jpeg" height="2089" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Diagram shows the procedure for autologous fat grafting. Liposuction of the lower abdomen or thigh is performed, followed by centrifugation of the adipocytes and their injection into the breast. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r46" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r46">46</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig8.jpeg" height="695" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Retromammary fat grafting. Non–fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction images in a 28-year-old woman before (left) and after (right) autologous fat grafting show expansion of the retromammary fat layer with resultant anterior parenchymal displacement. The grafted fat blends with the native retromammary fat (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig9.jpeg" height="1082" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Autologous fat grafting for primary breast augmentation. Mediolateral oblique mammograms of the right breast in a 36-year-old woman before (left) and after (right) fat grafting show an apparent decrease in breast density. This finding reflects numerous injection sites, in which small aliquots of fat are injected throughout the breast, with resulting numerous round or oval lucencies with thin capsules. The lucencies are oil cysts, a form of fat necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig10a.jpeg" height="1334" width="538" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Autologous fat grafting after right lumpectomy and radiation therapy in a 58-year-old woman with a remote history of right breast reduction mammoplasty. Fat grafting was performed to correct a deformity at the lumpectomy site. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammograms show the lumpectomy site before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> autologous fat grafting. <b>(c)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram obtained 3 years after <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a large area of fat necrosis, seen as dystrophic calcification at the fat grafting site.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig10b.jpeg" height="1334" width="494" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Autologous fat grafting after right lumpectomy and radiation therapy in a 58-year-old woman with a remote history of right breast reduction mammoplasty. Fat grafting was performed to correct a deformity at the lumpectomy site. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammograms show the lumpectomy site before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> autologous fat grafting. <b>(c)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram obtained 3 years after <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a large area of fat necrosis, seen as dystrophic calcification at the fat grafting site.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig10c.jpeg" height="1334" width="518" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Autologous fat grafting after right lumpectomy and radiation therapy in a 58-year-old woman with a remote history of right breast reduction mammoplasty. Fat grafting was performed to correct a deformity at the lumpectomy site. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammograms show the lumpectomy site before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> autologous fat grafting. <b>(c)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram obtained 3 years after <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> shows a large area of fat necrosis, seen as dystrophic calcification at the fat grafting site.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig11.jpeg" height="518" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> MR imaging findings in a 50-year-old woman who presented with two palpable right breast lumps after autologous fat grafting. Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR subtraction image (left) shows a lobulated hypointense mass with a thin enhancing rim in the retromammary fat (arrow). Sagittal non–fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image (right) shows that the rim-enhancing mass (arrow) exhibits the signal intensity of fat, a finding compatible with an oil cyst or fat necrosis. Anterior to this mass, an additional nonenhancing hyperintense mass is seen on both images (arrowhead), a finding compatible with an oil cyst or fat necrosis related to fat injection within the breast parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig12.jpeg" height="1234" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Diagrams show NAC reconstruction after mastectomy. A trilobed flap consisting of skin and subcutaneous fat (left) is sutured to form a nipple (right). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r32" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r32">32</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig13a.jpeg" height="848" width="880" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Skin-sparing mastectomy, autologous flap reconstruction, and NAC reconstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Preoperative <b>(a)</b> and postoperative <b>(b)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR subtraction images show that the typical imaging appearance of the NAC in <b>a</b> is absent in <b>b</b>. The postoperative nipple has minimal projection, with an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin. <b>(c)</b> Postoperative sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows retroareolar hyperintensity (arrow), a finding that may be related to subcutaneous fat incorporation into the NAC reconstruction flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig13b.jpeg" height="849" width="694" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Skin-sparing mastectomy, autologous flap reconstruction, and NAC reconstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Preoperative <b>(a)</b> and postoperative <b>(b)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR subtraction images show that the typical imaging appearance of the NAC in <b>a</b> is absent in <b>b</b>. The postoperative nipple has minimal projection, with an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin. <b>(c)</b> Postoperative sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows retroareolar hyperintensity (arrow), a finding that may be related to subcutaneous fat incorporation into the NAC reconstruction flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig13c.jpeg" height="1172" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Skin-sparing mastectomy, autologous flap reconstruction, and NAC reconstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Preoperative <b>(a)</b> and postoperative <b>(b)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR subtraction images show that the typical imaging appearance of the NAC in <b>a</b> is absent in <b>b</b>. The postoperative nipple has minimal projection, with an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin. <b>(c)</b> Postoperative sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows retroareolar hyperintensity (arrow), a finding that may be related to subcutaneous fat incorporation into the NAC reconstruction flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig14a.jpeg" height="1031" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> MR imaging findings in a 49-year-old woman who had previously undergone left mastectomy with left silicone-implant reconstruction and concomitant right silicone-implant augmentation for symmetry. Years later, the patient developed IDC and ductal carcinoma in situ in the right breast that were occult at mammography but were seen at MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows a 5-cm area of segmental nonmass enhancement adjacent to the implant capsule in the right breast. Because the tumor was 3 cm from the nipple, the patient was eligible for nipple-sparing mastectomy. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative <b>(b)</b> and postoperative <b>(c)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction images show preservation of the native NAC, with the classic peripheral enhancement pattern. <b>(d)</b> For comparison, in a sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image of the contralateral breast (nipple reconstruction was performed after the original mastectomy), the reconstructed NAC shows an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig14b.jpeg" height="1031" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> MR imaging findings in a 49-year-old woman who had previously undergone left mastectomy with left silicone-implant reconstruction and concomitant right silicone-implant augmentation for symmetry. Years later, the patient developed IDC and ductal carcinoma in situ in the right breast that were occult at mammography but were seen at MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows a 5-cm area of segmental nonmass enhancement adjacent to the implant capsule in the right breast. Because the tumor was 3 cm from the nipple, the patient was eligible for nipple-sparing mastectomy. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative <b>(b)</b> and postoperative <b>(c)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction images show preservation of the native NAC, with the classic peripheral enhancement pattern. <b>(d)</b> For comparison, in a sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image of the contralateral breast (nipple reconstruction was performed after the original mastectomy), the reconstructed NAC shows an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig14c.jpeg" height="977" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> MR imaging findings in a 49-year-old woman who had previously undergone left mastectomy with left silicone-implant reconstruction and concomitant right silicone-implant augmentation for symmetry. Years later, the patient developed IDC and ductal carcinoma in situ in the right breast that were occult at mammography but were seen at MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows a 5-cm area of segmental nonmass enhancement adjacent to the implant capsule in the right breast. Because the tumor was 3 cm from the nipple, the patient was eligible for nipple-sparing mastectomy. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative <b>(b)</b> and postoperative <b>(c)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction images show preservation of the native NAC, with the classic peripheral enhancement pattern. <b>(d)</b> For comparison, in a sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image of the contralateral breast (nipple reconstruction was performed after the original mastectomy), the reconstructed NAC shows an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig14d.jpeg" height="977" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span> MR imaging findings in a 49-year-old woman who had previously undergone left mastectomy with left silicone-implant reconstruction and concomitant right silicone-implant augmentation for symmetry. Years later, the patient developed IDC and ductal carcinoma in situ in the right breast that were occult at mammography but were seen at MR imaging. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image shows a 5-cm area of segmental nonmass enhancement adjacent to the implant capsule in the right breast. Because the tumor was 3 cm from the nipple, the patient was eligible for nipple-sparing mastectomy. <b>(b, c)</b> Preoperative <b>(b)</b> and postoperative <b>(c)</b> sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR subtraction images show preservation of the native NAC, with the classic peripheral enhancement pattern. <b>(d)</b> For comparison, in a sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image of the contralateral breast (nipple reconstruction was performed after the original mastectomy), the reconstructed NAC shows an enhancement pattern similar to that of the adjacent skin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig15.jpeg" height="1186" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Implant rupture in a 62-year-old woman who underwent silicone-implant augmentation 27 years previously. Axial short inversion time inversion-recovery silicone-excited image (top) shows bilateral intracapsular ruptures with bilateral linguini and keyhole signs (arrows). Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (bottom) fails to demonstrate intracapsular rupture and highlights the need for dedicated silicone-sensitive MR imaging sequences. We routinely tape silicone and saline phantoms (seen at center) to the bottom of the breast coil when evaluating for implant rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig16a.jpeg" height="446" width="952" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Reduction mammoplasty. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows vertical (left) and inverted-T (right) skin incisions (red outlines). <b>(b, c)</b> Intraoperative photographs of bilateral reduction mammoplasty show the vertical scar technique. In <b>b</b>, the left breast has been reduced in volume with a lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision, and periareolar and vertical skin incisions have been made in the right breast just before breast tissue removal. In <b>c</b>, the NAC is attached to the ducts and vascular supply via a pedicle and is repositioned superiorly. <b>(d)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the right breast in a 66-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows periareolar and dermal calcification, retroareolar fibrotic bands, and nipple elevation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image in a 45-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows a predominance of breast parenchymal tissue in the inferior dependent portion of the breast. Parenchymal redistribution is seen postoperatively because of resection of the subcutaneous fat. Note the skin thickening in the inferior area of the central breast, a finding related to the vertical scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig16b.jpeg" height="446" width="723" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Reduction mammoplasty. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows vertical (left) and inverted-T (right) skin incisions (red outlines). <b>(b, c)</b> Intraoperative photographs of bilateral reduction mammoplasty show the vertical scar technique. In <b>b</b>, the left breast has been reduced in volume with a lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision, and periareolar and vertical skin incisions have been made in the right breast just before breast tissue removal. In <b>c</b>, the NAC is attached to the ducts and vascular supply via a pedicle and is repositioned superiorly. <b>(d)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the right breast in a 66-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows periareolar and dermal calcification, retroareolar fibrotic bands, and nipple elevation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image in a 45-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows a predominance of breast parenchymal tissue in the inferior dependent portion of the breast. Parenchymal redistribution is seen postoperatively because of resection of the subcutaneous fat. Note the skin thickening in the inferior area of the central breast, a finding related to the vertical scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig16c.jpeg" height="875" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Reduction mammoplasty. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows vertical (left) and inverted-T (right) skin incisions (red outlines). <b>(b, c)</b> Intraoperative photographs of bilateral reduction mammoplasty show the vertical scar technique. In <b>b</b>, the left breast has been reduced in volume with a lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision, and periareolar and vertical skin incisions have been made in the right breast just before breast tissue removal. In <b>c</b>, the NAC is attached to the ducts and vascular supply via a pedicle and is repositioned superiorly. <b>(d)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the right breast in a 66-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows periareolar and dermal calcification, retroareolar fibrotic bands, and nipple elevation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image in a 45-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows a predominance of breast parenchymal tissue in the inferior dependent portion of the breast. Parenchymal redistribution is seen postoperatively because of resection of the subcutaneous fat. Note the skin thickening in the inferior area of the central breast, a finding related to the vertical scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig16d.jpeg" height="875" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> Reduction mammoplasty. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows vertical (left) and inverted-T (right) skin incisions (red outlines). <b>(b, c)</b> Intraoperative photographs of bilateral reduction mammoplasty show the vertical scar technique. In <b>b</b>, the left breast has been reduced in volume with a lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision, and periareolar and vertical skin incisions have been made in the right breast just before breast tissue removal. In <b>c</b>, the NAC is attached to the ducts and vascular supply via a pedicle and is repositioned superiorly. <b>(d)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the right breast in a 66-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows periareolar and dermal calcification, retroareolar fibrotic bands, and nipple elevation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image in a 45-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows a predominance of breast parenchymal tissue in the inferior dependent portion of the breast. Parenchymal redistribution is seen postoperatively because of resection of the subcutaneous fat. Note the skin thickening in the inferior area of the central breast, a finding related to the vertical scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig16e.jpeg" height="1002" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16e</span> Reduction mammoplasty. <b>(a)</b> Diagram shows vertical (left) and inverted-T (right) skin incisions (red outlines). <b>(b, c)</b> Intraoperative photographs of bilateral reduction mammoplasty show the vertical scar technique. In <b>b</b>, the left breast has been reduced in volume with a lollipop-shaped vertical skin incision, and periareolar and vertical skin incisions have been made in the right breast just before breast tissue removal. In <b>c</b>, the NAC is attached to the ducts and vascular supply via a pedicle and is repositioned superiorly. <b>(d)</b> Mediolateral oblique mammogram of the right breast in a 66-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows periareolar and dermal calcification, retroareolar fibrotic bands, and nipple elevation. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted MR image in a 45-year-old woman after reduction mammoplasty shows a predominance of breast parenchymal tissue in the inferior dependent portion of the breast. Parenchymal redistribution is seen postoperatively because of resection of the subcutaneous fat. Note the skin thickening in the inferior area of the central breast, a finding related to the vertical scar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig16e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig17a.jpeg" height="1134" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Imaging findings after reduction mammoplasty in the right breast of a 70-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Lateromedial mammogram shows linear skin thickening along the posterior portion of the right breast, outlined with scar markers. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows enhancement of the inframammary fold and skin at 6 o’clock and a focus of susceptibility artifact (arrow), a finding compatible with hypertrophic scarring (keloids) from reduction mammoplasty.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135059/asset/images/large/rg.343135059.fig17b.jpeg" height="1134" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Imaging findings after reduction mammoplasty in the right breast of a 70-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Lateromedial mammogram shows linear skin thickening along the posterior portion of the right breast, outlined with scar markers. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows enhancement of the inframammary fold and skin at 6 o’clock and a focus of susceptibility artifact (arrow), a finding compatible with hypertrophic scarring (keloids) from reduction mammoplasty.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135059&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Howlader N, Noone AM, Krapcho M, et al., eds. SEER cancer statistics review, 1975–2009 (vintage 2009 populations) [database online]. Bethesda, Md: National Cancer Institute, 2012. <a href="http://seer.cancer.gov/csr/1975_2009_pops09/">http://seer.cancer.gov/csr/1975_2009_pops09/</a>. Published 2012. Accessed August 21, 2012.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=SEER+cancer+statistics+review%2C+1975%E2%80%932009+%28vintage+2009+populations%29+%5Bdatabase+online%5D&amp;author=N+Howlader&amp;author=AM+Noone&amp;author=M+Krapcho&amp;publication_year=2012">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dragun AE, Huang B, Tucker TC, Spanos WJ. Increasing mastectomy rates among all age groups for early stage breast cancer: a 10-year study of surgical choice. <em>Breast J</em> 2012;18(4):318–325.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1524-4741.2012.01245.x">Crossref</a></div><div cla